commText: Fraser-McGurk and Abishek Porel are at the crease. Fraser-McGurk is on strike. Boult will open the attack
Boult to Fraser-McGurk, 2 runs, interesting angle to start with. Angling in on the pads, JFM gets a bit of a leading edge trying to flick, clears square leg though and goes in the gap for two
Boult to Fraser-McGurk, no run, oh beaten! A wild slog across the line and it's not bounced much either. Back of a length just outside off stump, JFM looks to slog and misses

Boult to Fraser-McGurk, no run, thuds the pad! This is brilliant bowling. First real test for JFM in this comp. Bowlers have fed him in the arc and the V, but Boult and RR have worked out a plan to cut the angle from round the wicket. They also have two catching men in the deep. And Boult is cramping him for room every ball, which is making the batter very uncomfortable. This swing in slightly so miss the lofted on-drive, didn't pick the line at all and gets hit on the pad. Will miss leg stump easily, may have been an edge onto pad as well

Boult to Fraser-McGurk, no run, now gets hit on the box. He's down in serious pain. The physio rushes. Clearly JFM isn't going to be offered anything in the slot for his to access that shot down the ground. Even if the length is full it is still cramping him for room because of Boult's cunning angle from round the wicket. JFM loves to loft in the V down the ground, but he's being tested properly tonight. Tried to smack this on the leg-side one-handed, missed and got hit

Boult to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, brilliant batting! He was trying to clear his front leg out and access leg-side, now he makes the change of backing away and making room to play that favourite lofted shot of his and he nails the off-drive over the infield. That will make him feel better
First innings scores in Delhi this season 266/7 - SRH vs DC 257/4 - DC vs MI 224/4 - DC vs GT Avg 1st innings score: 249
Boult to Fraser-McGurk, no run, inside-edge now as Boult drags the length back slightly, rolls to square leg
Sandeep Sharma, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, 1 run, slower delivery outside off stump, Abishek pushes it to short-cover
Stat: 89 sixes were hit across the first three matches in Delhi this season, which is roughly a six in every eight legal balls.
Sandy could target JFM with the inswinger. And they have a long-on very straight this is really good field placing from RR
Sandeep Sharma to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, oh he bowls the knuckle ball slower delivery, JFM wisely just checks the drive to long-on without going for the loft
Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, no run, steps out and dashes the cover drive, shame he picked out the fielder. Was a big gap on offer either side
Sanju up to the stumps

Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, FOUR, shot! Shouts of catch it from Sanju as Abishek checks the lofted drive, but Abishek managed to place it well wide of the mid-off fielder to the left and it runs away to the boundary. Hit that on the rise and got good value
Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, no run, now drives straight to mid-off along the ground

Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, FOUR, now a brilliant punch-drive from Abishek. Short of a length outside off stump, not much swing, Abishek hits down the ground through the line and mid-off had no chance to the left. These shots will ease pressure on JFM

Boult to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, you might use your smarts and plan lines and fields to stop me but I will still back my strenghts and try to do my best says JFM. He knew what Boult was upto - to cramp him for room. So he backed away early to give soom room and played his favourite lofted straight drive and hits the sightscreen

Boult to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, now he's forced Boult to go over the wicket. That's a mini battle won. Was short of a length but JFM backed away to slash hard, toe-end of the bat and it clears the short third man fielder
Boult to Fraser-McGurk, no run, shortish delivery outside off stump, JFM swings and misses

Boult to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, round the wicket again from Boult, but the length was too short and JFM could easily slap it over cover though it forced a bit of a mishit. Went over the infield and picked up four more
Boult to Fraser-McGurk, no run, short delivery, JFM swings and gets hit on the body. But he seems fine
Boult to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, geos for a big swing again, inside edge rolls to mid-wicket and he will keep strike
Avesh Khan, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack

Avesh Khan to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, bold full delivery on the stumps from Avesh Khan. Fraser-McGurk goes for a big loft down the ground, gets lucky with a thick inside edge that escapes Sanju's dive to the left

Avesh Khan to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, stand and deliver! Interestingly Avesh keeps it full again when that's what JFM is looking for. This time stand and deliver stuff as he stays leg-side of this slot ball and hammers the cover drive wide of extra-cover

Avesh Khan to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, hat-trick of fours as JFM slices this over backward point. Third freebie full ball from Avesh Khan and JFM cashed in big time. Poorly thoughout over from Avesh Khan offering everything in JFM's strong zone. This one had width, so the batter sliced it over the infield

Avesh Khan to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, he goes pace off and into the wicket but it sits up with width and JFM muscles the lofted drive over long-off for a flatish six. Sanju immediately runs to the bowler to have a chat

Avesh Khan to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, he's unstoppable, this young lad! Length delivery outside off stump, JFM gets yet another gift dished out with so much width and he hits that on the rise for a flat lofted hit over cover. It landed just an inch inside the rope. Looked six for most parts of that travel

Avesh Khan to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, this is a really poor over from Avesh Khan. Now he dishes out a full toss and made life even easier for JFM. Didn't even try to hit it too hard and he sends this soaring over mid-wicket. Davey Warner is up from his seat and applauding that 19-ball fifty with a big smile from the dressing room. 28 off that over from Avesh. An over that didn't have proper plan or understanding of what the batter was capable of doing
Ravichandran Ashwin, right-arm off break, comes into the attack
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, 1 run, flatter delivery, nudged to mid-wicket
Ashwin to Fraser-McGurk, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ashwin to Fraser-McGurk, out Caught by Ferreira!! Oh in the airrrr and straight to cover. Wry smile of Ashwin's face because he knew he got lucky big time. He once said how he got Sehwag out by bowling rubblish balls and although unintentional here it has worked again. High full toss that even Ashwin had to take a second look at the ump to see if it was below waist, it was a fair delivery, surprised JFM tried to smack it over the infield and picked out cover to perfection. Brilliant innings ends. Fraser-McGurk c Ferreira b Ashwin 50(20) [4s-7 6s-3]
Shai Hope, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Ashwin to Shai Hope, 1 run, turning back in, pushed to long-on
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, SIX, oh shot! Short delivery, Abishek goes deep in the crease and thumps this pull off the back foot and smacks it over mid-wicket for a maximum
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, no run, thuds the pad as he fails to read that slider, wasn't good enough for LBW shout though
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, 1 run, nudged to mid-wicket
Shai Hope could be unlucky with a runout at the bowler's end. Oh he's not even in the frame! GONE!
Sandeep Sharma [1.0-0-10-0] is back into the attack
Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, THATS OUT!! Run Out!!

Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, out Shai Hope Run Out!! What were you doing backing up so far, Shai Hope? This was a smashed straight drive that Sandeep Sharma tried to field, stuck his left hand out and got a deflection on it. Ball crashed into the stumps with Hope almost two feet out of the crease. Sandeep knew he had his man, Hope knew his fate and walked off. Shai Hope run out (Sandeep Sharma) 1(1)
Axar Patel, left handed bat, comes to the crease

Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, FOUR, slogged over mid-wicket and it's four more. Still has the mindset to maximize the final over of the powerplay despite two quick wickets. Short of a length delivery, Abishek lifts it over mid-wicket and gets the boundary
Sandeep Sharma to Abishek Porel, 1 run, advances and yorks himself up. drilled to long-on
Sandeep Sharma to Axar, no run, let me get a sighter kind of defence back to the bowler from Sandeep Sharma
Sandeep Sharma to Axar, FOUR, oh inside edge past the stumps. Axar made room for a big smash over cover, thick edge escapes the stumps and the keeper to the right
Sandeep Sharma to Axar, 1 run, slower delivery, Axar taps it to point

Highlights (overs 1-6): -- 4 dots in the opening over from Boult -- Abishek Porel gets going with a couple of boundaries -- Fraser-McGurk smashes Boult for 15 off his 2nd over -- 4 4 4 6 4 6 - Fraser-McGurk tonks Avesh Khan to all corners to bring up a 19-ball fifty -- Ashwin gets rid of Fraser-McGurk with a high full toss
Great powerplay but they would have liked to lose one wicket lesser.
Oh Riyan in with two LHBs batting
Riyan Parag, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Riyan Parag to Axar, 1 run, flighted delivery on the stumps, Axar works it to long-on

Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, FOUR, goes for the slog-sweep, bit of a top edge, big top edge in fact but he managed to clear the short fine leg fielder and gets four. Low full toss, Abishek gets it to the long leg fence
Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, no run, oh leading edge as he troubles Abishek with turn. Wasn't short enough for a flick off the back foot, lucky it didn't carry to backward point
Jake Fraser-McGurk in the Powerplay in IPL 2024 Runs: 245 Balls: 96 Dismissals: 4 Avg: 61.2 SR: 255.2 4s/6s: 29/19
Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, no run, oh almost snuck that through the gate with a slider, rushed cut shot to backward point
Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, no run, now he slips this between the batters legs. Slider down leg, Abishek misses the flick, ball goes through the batter and past the leg stump
Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, 1 run, manages to send it to deep mid-wicket
RR call for an early timeout. This pitch is aiding some turn. Chahal will be a key bowler for RR. DC need a minimum of 190 here
Highest Powerplay scores for DC in the IPL 92/0 vs MI, Delhi, 2024 88/2 vs SRH, Delhi, 2024 81/0 vs PBKS, Brabourne, 2022 78/2 vs RR, Delhi, 2024 71/0 vs RCB, Bengaluru, 2008
Yuzvendra Chahal, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack

Chahal to Abishek Porel, SIX, what a shot from Abishek Porel. This lad has been oustanding to watch for his intent. Flighted delivery on the stumps, probably knows Chahal isn't going to the bowl the googly, so he steps out, gets to the pitch of the ball and whips it out of sight over mid-wicket. Flat hit lands on the rope
Chahal to Abishek Porel, 1 run, very brave follow up from Chahal. Tossed it up on the stumps inviting the big hit again, Abishek calmly wrists it to mid-wicket
Chahal to Axar, 1 run, nudged to mid-wicket
Chahal to Abishek Porel, no run, shortish and outside off stump, Abishek cuts really well, backward point does well to save four

Fastest IPL fifties for DC (by balls taken) 15 - Jake Fraser-McGurk vs SRH, Delhi, 2024 15 - Jake Fraser-McGurk vs MI, Delhi, 2024 17 - Chris Morris vs GL, Delhi, 2016 18 - Rishabh Pant vs MI, Mumbai WS, 2019 18 - Prithvi Shaw vs KKR, Ahmedabad, 2021 19 - Tristan Stubbs vs MI, Mumbai WS, 2024 19 - Jake Fraser-McGurk vs RR, Delhi, 2024
Chahal to Abishek Porel, 2 runs, oh cracking off-drive, long-off runs to the right and slides to save two runs. That's two boundaries denied by the RR fielders

Chahal to Abishek Porel, FOUR, now the sweep to deep backward square leg, Boult slides and pushes it back. That's three fours saved. Oh hang on, the back foot could be in contact with the rope. Yes, it's a four. Poor ball down leg and Abishek swept it away for four
Riyan Parag to Axar, 1 run, flatter delivery, wristed to mid-wicket
Most IPL fifties scored in less than 20 balls 3 - Jake Fraser-McGurk 2 - Yashasvi Jaiswal 2 - Nicholas Pooran 2 - Ishan Kishan 2 - Sunil Narine 2 - Kieron Pollard 2 - Travis Head 2 - KL Rahul
Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, 1 run, drives down the ground to long-off
Riyan Parag to Axar, wide, fired down leg
Riyan Parag to Axar, no run, shortish delivery, Axar punches it off the back foot to cover
Riyan Parag to Axar, 1 run, fullish delivery, Axar drives to long-off
Riyan Parag to Abishek Porel, 1 run, on the leg stump, Abishek wrists this to mid-wicket
Stat: McGurk is also the only one to score two IPL fifties in 15 balls or fewer.
Riyan Parag to Axar, SIX, Axar pounces on the slot ball and smacks it over long-on. Riyan Parag was doing a great job until this ball that he slightly overpitched and allowed the batter to get under

Chahal off the attack with two LHBs at the crease. He's a brave bowler and tosses it up and teases the batter even if he gets hit. Very good bowler to RHBs, does get turn, but the fact that he hardly bowls the googly to LHBs and mainly tries to bowl wide of off as defence is hampering him and captains are pushed a bit extra to manage him when two LHBs are the crease.
Ravichandran Ashwin [1.0-0-9-1] is back into the attack
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, 1 run, worked away to mid-wicket
DC batters with 50-plus scores within the powerplay \n78*(24) - Jake Fraser-McGurk vs MI, Delhi, 2024 \n50(20) - Jake Fraser-McGurk vs RR, Delhi, 2024
Ashwin to Axar, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ashwin to Axar, out Caught by Riyan Parag!! In the airrr and straight to long-off. Flighted delivery outside off stump, Axar tried to loft down the ground, hit it flat and picked out Riyan. Ashwin gets his second of the night. Axar c Riyan Parag b Ashwin 15(10) [4s-1 6s-1]
Rishabh Pant, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Ashwin to Pant, 1 run, flat from Ashwin, pushed to mid-on
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, 1 run, shortish delivery, Abishek works it to deep mid-wicket
Ashwin to Pant, 1 run, short and down leg, Pant pulls to deep backward square leg, Boult had it covered but a bad bounce meant he had to put the body behind the line as second line of defence
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, 2 runs, full delivery outside off stump, Abishek leans forward and drives nicely wide of mid-off, lovely work to the right from long-off to cut this off again
Avesh Khan [1.0-0-28-0] is back into the attack
Avesh Khan to Pant, 1 run, dragged to deep square leg
Axar vs Ashwin in the IPL Runs: 8 Balls: 19 Dismissals: 3 SR: 42.1 Avg: 2.67 Dots: 12

Avesh Khan to Abishek Porel, SIX, pulled away over mid-wicket and Abishek Porel gets his first fifty of the season. Give this lad a good, long run please. He has a very good range and intent. Shortish delivery, Abishek pulls and clears mid-wicket. Delhi crowd and management applaud that effort and he raises the bat
Avesh Khan to Abishek Porel, 1 run, full and wide of off stump Abishek slices it to deep backward point
Avesh Khan to Pant, 1 run, short of length delivery, Pant punches it to cover-point
Avesh Khan to Abishek Porel, FOUR, full toss, Abishek drives wide of cover past Ashwin and it's four more. Tried the yorker and missed it by a distance
Avesh Khan to Abishek Porel, 1 run, on-drive to long-on and keeps strike
Trent Boult [2.0-0-21-0] is back into the attack
Boult to Abishek Porel, 1 run, shortish delivery, Abishek pulls it to deep mid-wicket. Was the slower delivery and he lost a bit of shape trying to hit too hard

Boult to Pant, 1 run, just too much fancy stuff from Pant there for a run. Stayed inside the line and played a stylish helicopter like flick, thankfully didn't hit it straight to deep mid-wicket, could have been caught otherwise. He it to the left of the fielder and got one
Boult to Abishek Porel, FOUR, Abishek plays the conventional pull shot and powers it to the riight of deep mid-wicket for a one bounce four
Boult to Abishek Porel, 1 run, squeezed away to cover
Boult to Pant, SIX, poor ball from Boult with fine leg up. Pant moves off-side to scoop it over the infield and he middles it so well to clear the fine leg rope
Boult to Pant, no run, Boult goes wide of off stump, Pant looks to drive and misses
Ravichandran Ashwin [2.0-0-15-2] is back into the attack
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, 1 run, shortish delivery, Abishek slices it to short third man

Ashwin to Pant, no run, appeal for LBW, not given. They reckon missing leg so they don't opt for the review. Slider on the stumps, Pant goes inside the line and looks to sweep, overbalances and falls like he usually does, impact on leg stump and good of the ump, bowler and keeper to judge that it was missing leg easily
Ashwin to Pant, 1 run, flatter delivery on the stumps, Pant works it to mid-wicket
Ashwin to Abishek Porel, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ashwin to Abishek Porel, out Caught by Sandeep Sharma!! In the airrr and the third for Ashwin. 95ks on this offie, Abishek backs away for a lofted inside out drive, slices it completely and backward point has it so easy. End of a brilliant innings from Abishek Porel. Put on a bold face and took the bowlers on even if wickets fell. Abishek Porel c Sandeep Sharma b Ashwin 65(36) [4s-7 6s-3]
Tristan Stubbs, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Ashwin to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, slider outside off stump, Stubbs knocks it to cover
Ashwin to Pant, 1 run, slow and short down leg, Pant nudges to square leg and it's a single. Three gold overs from Ashwin so far, just 19 runs and 3 wickets in it when the run rate is over 11
Yuzvendra Chahal [1.0-0-14-0] is back into the attack
Chahal to Pant, 1 run, quick and flat outside off on a length, Pant hangs back and knocks it down to long-on
Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, tossed up full ball outside off, Tristan Stubbs leans ahead and eases it through covers
Chahal to Pant, 1 run, 89.2kph full ball on middle and off, Pant works it through mid-wicket. The batters think about the second but it's not on
Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, floated nicely on off on a fuller length, turning away, Tristan Stubbs strokes it to cover-point. 150 up for DC
Chahal to Pant, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Chahal to Pant, out Caught by Boult!! Pant looked ugly while playing that shot and he pays the price for it! Samuel Badree on air mentions that Chahal becomes the first Indian bowler to take 350 T20 wickets! A fuller length ball on middle and leg, Pant got down and tried to hit it across but didn't have any sort of balance while playing that. Had he stayed put the slog-sweep was an easy connect, but that's how plays. He's won games playing atrocious shots and he's irked his mates doing the same too. Ended up mistiming it towards deep backward square leg and Boult took an easy catch. Pant c Boult b Chahal 15(13) [6s-1]
Gulbadin Naib, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Chahal to Gulbadin, 1 run, bowls the googly and it's slow through the air outside off, Gulbadin pushes at it tentatively and gets an inside edge towards short fine. A good comeback over from Chahal
Ashwin to Gulbadin, 1 run, quick and flat on middle and leg, Gulbadin works it to mid-wicket for a single
Ashwin to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, bowls the in-drifter on middle and leg, Tristan Stubbs flicks it with the angle through mid-wicket. The fielder from the deep is quick to deny them the second
Ashwin to Gulbadin, 1 run, 93.1kph back of a length ball outside off, knocked down to long-off
Ashwin to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, full ball fired in at 98.7kph on off, Tristan Stubbs strokes it down to long-off
Ashwin to Gulbadin, no run, slower through the air and on a length on off, Gulbadin is caught in the crease and blocks it tentatively
Ashwin to Gulbadin, 1 run, 91.4kph back of a length ball on off, Gulbadin camps back and works it towards wide long-on. End of a brilliant spell from Ashwin. He ends with figures of 4-0-24-3

HIghlights (Overs 7-15): -- Chahal concedes 14 off his opening over -- Ashwin nips out Axar in his 2nd over -- Porel brings up a 28-ball fifty, his 1st of the season -- Boult goes for 13 in his 3rd over -- Ashwin gets his 3rd; dismisses the dangerou-looking Porel -- Chahal removes the DC skipper in his 2nd over

Time for the strategic break! Spin has helped RR to make some damage control. There's some turn and grip available and Ashwin used that to great effect. Chahal's remaining two overs will be crucial from the point of view of RR. Stubbs is out there and DC will want him to utilize the death overs
Chahal to Gulbadin, SIX, shot! A slot delivery drifting in on middle and leg, Gulbadin clears his front leg and smokes it over long-on for a maximum. Hit that hard and got the desired result
Chahal to Gulbadin, 1 run, 86.6kph back of a length ball and it's the wrong 'un on middle and leg, tucked around the corner
Pant vs Chahal in the IPL: Runs: 83 Balls: 59 Dismissals: 3 Avg: 27.66 SR: 140.67 4s/6s: 4/6
Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, no run, another googly and quicker through the air, Tristan Stubbs looks to flick it across but is struck on the pads. That was going down leg
Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, no run, floated delivery outside off, Tristan Stubbs pushes it to covers
Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, no run, on a back of a length on off, Tristan Stubbs doesn't have much space to work with and chops it to extra cover

Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, quicker and flatter, going down leg, Tristan Stubbs places it to to square leg to retain strike. Good comeback from Chahal after being hit for a six off the first ball of this over
Sandeep Sharma [2.0-0-20-0] is back into the attack
Sandeep Sharma to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, slower short of length ball outside off, the leg-cutter perhaps, Tristan Stubbs reaches out to it and pulls it to deep mid-wicket
Pant vs spin in IPL 2024: Runs: 131 Balls: 114 Dismissals: 5 (all against RA leg-spin) Avg: 26.2 SR: 114.91 4s/6s: 7/6 Dots: 40
Sandeep Sharma to Gulbadin, 1 run, on a length outside off, punched to mid-on
Sandeep Sharma to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, full ball angling in on middle and leg, Gulbadin flicks it to deep mid-wicket
Sandeep Sharma to Gulbadin, no run, an off-pace bouncer outside off, Gulbadin doesn't go after it
Sandeep Sharma to Gulbadin, no run, another slower bouncer just outside off, Gulbadin looks to pull it across but was early through his shot. The umpire signals two bouncers for the over
Sandeep Sharma to Gulbadin, 1 run, full ball shaping towards the leg-stump, Gulbadin can only flick it to deep square leg. Only 4 off the over, brilliant stuff from Sandeep Sharma

Chahal to Gulbadin, FOUR, on a back of a length outside off, Gulbadin has to fetch it from outside off and he slogs it towards wide long-on. The fielder in the deep moves to his right and dives but has no chance to stop it
Chahal to Gulbadin, 1 run, tossed up wide outside off, Gulbadin hits it towards long-off only for a single

Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, FOUR, that's innovative! Tristan Stubbs knew that backward point was up. He went for the reverse hit to the in-drifter and executed it brilliantly to hit it to the desired area
Deep backward point in place now

Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, FOUR, this is smart batting! Tristan Stubbs premeditated and shuffled across his stumps as he knew Chahal will bowl this one wide outside off. He kneels down on one knee and sweeps it past the fielder at square leg for another boundary
Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, 2 runs, short and wide outside off, Tristan Stubbs fetches it from there and flat-bats it towads wide long-on

Chahal to Tristan Stubbs, SIX, 21 off the over! Tristan Stubbs shuffled a bit across his stumps and Chahal bowled it full and into his arc. A slog-sweep played to perfection over deep square leg for a maximum. Just the kind of over DC wanted to tee off at the fag end
Trent Boult [3.0-0-34-0] is back into the attack
Boult to Gulbadin, 1 run, a low full-toss on off, hard to get underneath those. Gulbadin chips it towards long-on

Boult to Tristan Stubbs, FOUR, slower shortish ball shaping across Tristan Stubbs. He had ample time to size it up. Picked his spot and pulled it through mid-wicket to find the fence. This was a poor ball
Boult to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, a yorker length ball around the pads, Tristan Stubbs looks to flick and might have got an inside edge onto his boots as the ball rolled towards square leg
Boult to Gulbadin, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Boult to Gulbadin, out Caught by Ashwin!! The slower ball does the trick! An off-cutter on a length wide outside off, Gulbadin throws his bat at it but ends up getting a thick outside edge towards short third. Ashwin takes it safely. End of a decent partnership. Gulbadin c Ashwin b Boult 19(15) [4s-1 6s-1]
DC use their Impact sub - Rasikh Dar comes in for Abishek Porel
Rasikh Dar Salam, right handed bat, comes to the crease

Boult to Rasikh Salam, FOUR, the Impact sub makes an instant impact! Rasikh Salam shuffles across his stumps and Boult bowls it into his zone. Perfect length to play the scoop and he plays it nicely to fine leg for a boundary

Boult to Rasikh Salam, FOUR, this is some batting! Rasikh Salam premeditates as he shuffles across his stumps. This time Boult follows him nicely actually but the length allows Rasikh Salam to line it up. He manages to play it over the keeper to get the desired result. Thinking on his feet
Sandeep Sharma [3.0-0-24-0] is back into the attack

Sandeep Sharma to Tristan Stubbs, SIX, that's a brilliant hit! A low full-toss well outside off, not easy to hit those. Tristan Stubbs gets low in his stance which allows him to generate power. He hits it over deep extra cover for a maximum

Sandeep Sharma to Tristan Stubbs, SIX, Sandeep Sharma overcompensates and bowls a shortish delivery wide outside off. Tristan Stubbs uses his long reach and flat-bats it over the bowler's head for a flat maximum
Sandeep Sharma to Tristan Stubbs, THATS OUT!! Lbw!!

Sandeep Sharma to Tristan Stubbs, out Lbw!! Tristan Stubbs has been trapped in front but he takes the review! Looked plumb to the naked eye. Was the perfect yorker that seared in from around off, Stubbs tried to play it across but missed to get hit on the back leg. Time for the replays. Clearly no bat invovled says the third umpire. Over to ball-tracking and it returns three reds. It would have crashed into middle and leg. A breezy knock from Tristan Stubbs nonetheless. Tristan Stubbs lbw b Sandeep Sharma 41(20) [4s-3 6s-3]
Kuldeep Yadav, left handed bat, comes to the crease

Sandeep Sharma to Kuldeep Yadav, FOUR, A slower back of a length ball outside off, Kuldeep Yadav shuffles across his stumps and plays a pick up shot over backward square leg. The fielder moves to his left but to no avail
Sandeep Sharma to Kuldeep Yadav, 1 run, a low full-toss outside off, Kuldeep Yadav plays it off the back of his bat actually. It flies towards short third. Chahal dives but it lands just short of him
Sandeep Sharma to Rasikh Salam, THATS OUT!! Run Out!!

Sandeep Sharma to Rasikh Salam, out Rasikh Salam Run Out!! 1 run completed! Slower short ball outside off, Rasikh Salam mistimes his pull over mid-wicket. The throw comes in flat towards Samson and he takes the bails off - Rasikh Salam is not even in the frame. DC finish with 221/8. Rasikh Salam run out (Shubham Dubey/Samson) 9(3) [4s-2]

21:13 Local Time, 15:43 GMT, 21:13 IST: The 200-mark has been breached for the fourth consecutive time in the first innings in Delhi this season. Samson chose to bowl after winning the toss but Fraser McGurk went beserk in the powerplay to put the opposition under immense pressure. The Australian scored a 19-ball fifty. But, it was a full-toss from Ashwin which got rid of him. An unfortunate run-out of Hope occurred in quick succession. Porel took over and started finding boundaries consistently. Axar played the supporting role to him but couldn't convert his start. Pant also misfired and fell while playing a poor shot. Ashwin bowled a brilliant spell tonight and ended with miserly figures of 4-0-24-3. It was the cameo from Stubbs in the death overs which gave DC the much-needed momentum. Chahal wasn't his usual self as he couldn't utilize the helpful conditions on offer properly. 222 is certainly gettable but the teams batting first have won on every occasion so far. There's some turn and grip available and Axar and Kuldeep have a good amount of runs to play with. Will be an interesting battle...

Ravichandran Ashwin: Sometimes you have nights these like and you don't - bowl a full toss and get wickets. I have been working on a few things. Sometimes you find yourself wanting to search for more and more. This IPL season has been quite exceptional (in terms of being pushed to the limit). I have been working on different angles and releases. Got a couple of balls to hold. (On the total) Wouldn't say it is a par score. You need to bat really well, they got Kuldeep and Axar so how you manage them is key. You are probably going to see more baseballers playing cricket. I think in modern day T20 those good balls aren't good balls anymore (chuckles).
